<h1 style="text-align: center; color: white;"><span style="font-family: courier new, courier, monospace;">What is sampling and how does it affect sound quality?</span></h1>
<h2 style="text-align: center; color: white;"><span style="background-color: #ffffff; color: #000000;"><em><span style="font-family: book antiqua, palatino, serif;">&nbsp;Amy Plewnik&nbsp; <br /></span></em></span></h2>
<p style="color: white; padding: 0px 300px; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: courier new, courier, monospace;">Sampling is the process used to turn analogue signals to digital sound. The sound is split up into small time intervals. At each specified time interval, the amplitude of the sound wave is measured.</span></p>
<p style="color: white; padding: 0px 300px; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: courier new, courier, monospace;">A time interval of 0.5 seconds will not give an accurate representation of the original audio, resulting in reduced sound quality. When this interval is smaller, it more closely resembles the original audio as it is taking more samples.</span></p>
<p style="color: white; padding: 0px 300px; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: courier new, courier, monospace;">Then the maximum voltage range of the analogue sound is divided into a number of discrete voltage bands. A number represents each band, the samples are mapped onto these bands, giving us a digital numerical value to our analogue signal.</span></p>
<p style="color: white; padding: 0px 300px; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: courier new, courier, monospace;">Sound samples are usually assigned to 16-bit numbers representing the quantisation levels. A reliable and accurate digital copy will depend on how broad a range of numbers is available in the process.</span></p>
